You will want to convert you state into immutable object like:
const immutableState = Immutable.fromJS(yourState)

When working with immutableState you will have to use getters and setters. That might be annoying when doing some more complicated things. So you can call immutableState.toJS() and get the "normal" javascript object again. Calling toJS is not recommended. I would personally use it only in mapStateToProps function or in selectors.

